<h2 id="pascals-triangle-evened-out">Pascal‚Äôs Triangle evened out</h2>
<p>One of the most remarkable aspects of Pascal‚Äôs Triangle is how often it has appeared in different cultures and contexts and time periods. No person or society can claim ownership ‚Äì it is a truly human invention!</p>
<div class="pictures-container">
  <img src="../images/outreach/climbing_meru.png" class="shrinkToFit" height="300" />
</div>
<p>As with many mathematical objects, some of  the most interesting patterns in Pascal‚Äôs Triangle  emerge only when you ‚Äòforget‚Äô much of what you know about it.   To begin with, take a look at what happens when you examine just the odd entries of Pascal‚Äôs triangle.</p>

<div class="pictures-container">
 <img src="../images/outreach/mod_2_8_rows.png" class="shrinkToFit" height="150" />

 <img src="../images/outreach/mod_2_16_rows.png" class="shrinkToFit" height="150" />

 <img src="../images/outreach/mod_2_32_rows.png" class="shrinkToFit" height="150" />
 
</div>

<p>And this is just the beginning ‚Äì using modular arithmetic you can discover even more families of ‚Äòself-similar‚Äô fractals residing within.</p>

<p>For the sides to this talk <a href="../images/slides/pascal.pdf">click here</a>.</p>

<p>To try coloring Pascal‚Äôs triangle yourself, you can use  <a href="../images/worksheets/pascal.png">this blank template</a>
or this <a href="../images/worksheets/pascal_numbered.png">this numbered template</a></p>

